Apache NiFi is a data integration and automation platform designed to move and manage
data between systems in a reliable and controlled way. The fundamentals video explains
that NiFi follows a flow-based programming model, where data moves through a series of
connected processors on a user interface. Each piece of data traveling through the system
is called a FlowFile. A FlowFile contains both the actual data content and metadata
attributes that describe it. Processors act on FlowFiles to perform tasks such as generating
data, transforming formats, filtering records, routing based on conditions, or sending data
to external systems. This visual approach makes complex data pipelines easier to design,
monitor, and troubleshoot.

NiFi tracks every FlowFile as it moves through the system, providing detailed insight into
where the data came from, how it was transformed, and where it was sent. This
transparency is essential for debugging, auditing, and ensuring data governance standards
are met. The ability to monitor and trace data movement makes NiFi especially valuable in
environments where compliance and accountability are important.

These foundational concepts directly connect to this assignment because we are building
data flows in NiFi and integrating them with Solr. NiFi is responsible for generating and
processing log data, while Solr serves as the indexing and search engine that stores and
queries that data. By sending processed logs from NiFi into a Solr collection, we create a
complete data pipeline that automates ingestion and enables powerful search
capabilities. This demonstrates how NiFi and Solr work together to manage, process, and
analyze data efficiently in a real-world system.
